We sailed eastward from the African coastline across the vast Indian Ocean, arriving in the Maldives, a chain of islands composed of coral reefs.
During the constant stormy southwest monsoon season, manta rays living in the lagoon waters of the archipelago gather around a small island called Hanifaru.
Schools of tiny shrimp and crabs, most smaller than our pupils, form the primary diet of mantas.
When the plankton is more dispersed, mantas typically feed alone, rolling backward in the water like dogs chasing their own tails.
When the plankton becomes more concentrated, mantas start swimming in a head-to-t-head formation, creating a long feeding line. The delicious food missed by the leading manta is consumed by the following companions.
As the plankton in the bay accumulates, the mantas gather into tighter formations, a unique feeding method we refer to as "whirlpool feeding."
The mantas stack upon each other, forming a tight spiral vortex that sucks in the plankton, directly guiding it into the giant mouths of the mantas.
Diving amongst thousands of manta rays, an image that will stay with me forever.
When I first went to Hanifaru to take photos, it was had not yet been protected, and its ecosystem was under threat from local development.
Through collaborations with organizations like the Manta Trust, my photographs ultimately contributed to Hanifaru becoming an ocean sanctuary.
Fishermen on nearby islands, who had once hunted many manta rays for their skins to make traditional drums.
And now, they have become the most steadfast protectors of the manta rays, which annually bring over $8 million to the Maldives.
