This year, to fulfill my contract shoot for National Geographic, I came to the California Peninsula.
In the center of the peninsula, along the Pacific Ocean side, lies San Ignacio Lagoon, an important breeding ground for gray whales.
In the past century, this coastline served as a massive slaughterhouse, with over 20,000 gray whales being killed here, leaving only a few hundred survivors.
And now, these descendants of the gray whales will their calves to the surface, playfully interact with us, and even engage in playful behavior together.
This species has surprisingly recovered.
On the other side of the peninsula is Porme Cape, a tranquil fishing village.
Decades of overfishing had once pushed this village to the brink of bankruptcy.
In 1995, local fishermen convinced the government to designate this area as an ocean sanctuary.
What follows can truly be called a miracle.
In 2005, just after 10 years of protection, scientists found that the number of local fish had achieved a record-record recovery.
